Comment:
To Kevin Adler:

I was impressed and moved by your presentation at ADRx last Friday.

What resonated most with me was your narrative of the pain, emptiness, and abandonment one experiences with the loss of their social support system.

While your vivid stories were of those who are physically homeless, I couldn't help but feel that the same sense of isolation and marginalization can manifest for people who have lost their jobs, have had a love relationship disintegrate -- or who have been socially ostracized and outcast by communities they once belonged to.

Your presentation has given all of us something to reflect upon and to act on. Again, thank you for making ADRx a worthwhile experience!

-- Jeff Marson

Hello!

My name is Dylan Zhao and I am writing to apply for the virtual Program Internships FIND THEM and DIGITAL DETECTIVE. I am a freshman at UC Berkeley intending to major in Business or Economics, and I would love the privilege of a virtual internship at Miracle Messages this summer.

I learned about Miracle Messages when the founder and CEO Kevin Adler came to speak in my Political Science seminar. I was immediately struck by his statement that there has been a "systemic loss of compassion" within society, and I have since contemplated ways in which it can be brought back. This is what drove me to submit this application for an internship at Miracle Messages. I feel that if I can spend my summer helping people reconnect with their families, I will be doing my part to restore the compassion we have lost.

In terms of my credentials for the two positions, I offer:
- A background in both business and community service, as the past Vice President of Finance for a student-created non-profit retail company, and co-founder of the non-profit organization Objective Resolution Calgary (ORC), which introduced over 200 less-privileged youth to Model United Nations
- Outreach and marketing experience with the above two initiatives, in identifying customers, spreading social media and advertising campaigns, and, in the case of ORC, securing prolific guest speakers
- 6 years of experience in competitive debate and Model United Nations, developing my public speaking skills, communication, and ability to work in a team
- A solid educational and experiential foundation in accounting, finance, and business, as well as discussing such subjects on the national student publication, the “Intercollegiate Finance Journal”
- A history of excellent academic and workplace performance
- A genuine desire to help others and make my community (whether at school or home) a better place

I believe I have what it takes to consistently deliver on the responsibilities of a Program Intern (FIND THEM or DIGITAL DETECTIVE) at Miracle Messages. I can be reached at zhao.dylan@berkeley.edu, or by phone at 510-990-7878, and would be more than happy to submit a resume upon request. Thank you for your consideration.

Sincerely,
Dylan Zhao

My names Michaela Lumia and I'm a sophomore at Loyola Marymount University. I am a marketing major with a studio arts minor. I would love to work with Miracle Messages as a Story Telling Intern. I have always wanted to work for a non-profit, especially one related to homelessness. I'm from the east coast and I would visit New York City many times every year to see my Grandfather in Manhattan. I have a distinct memory from when I was probably 7 years old of a homeless man standing at the top of the subway stairs. I didn't really understand what homelessness was at the time. It was the middle of winter and he had no shoes. He was only wearing battered and torn white wool socks- the same type the my dad wears. Seeing him standing in the same socks as my dad stuck my heart. It made me realize that these homeless people are actual people with families and stories. What if that man had a daughter too? What if one day that was my dad standing there instead? At the time, that realization shocked me and filled me with sadness. Ever since then, I knew I wanted to do something to help people experiencing homelessness. I would love to be able to help in the best way I know how. Being a studio arts minor, I have a lot of experience in Adobe Suite and other video platforms. Hi Kevin

As I told you on our FB Messenger quick talk I am very interested to develop the idea of ​​Miracle Messages (which is wonderful and very powerful) in France.

The rate of French homeless is estimated at about 150,000, although no serious investigation has been conducted since 2012 on this subject. However, we know that this rate has increased by 50% in ten years in our country. I have also a personal story with this as I told you.

Also I'm working at developing and producing some social documentaries for TV and theater since one year with great and famous directors in France with my partner Julien Hossein. We think, with Julien, we can involve some celebrities from film, television, and the industrial world in France to this cause. For example, perhaps creating a homeless caring system by some of these personalities to attract even more the medias on Miracle Messages and then attract funding to help more and more homeless people reconnect with their families and loved ones.

We are also wondering whether it would not be interesting to extend this idea to the issue of migrants. In France and Europe, more and more people are now migrating from their home countries to our countries in order to flee tyrannical political regimes, climatic conditions of life that have become impossible, or extreme poverty.  Those people quickly lose sight of their families and loved ones and finally lives as homeless in our country. They might need to send Miracle Messages with our help too.

In order to create a Miracle Messages home in Paris/France, what do we need ? We need to know how you want to deal with that. Is there a ‘franchise’ to pay? Do we have the opportunity to create our own ideas to develop Miracle Messages in our country? What ‘business model’ do you operate on? And finally, we will need to know how surveys work to find homeless families and loved ones.

Looking foward to your reply.

Best regards,

Christophe Perie

Hello Miracle Messages Team,

My name is Erica Schwartzmann, and I am the Arizona State University & St. Vincent de Paul Program Manager.  Arizona State University (ASU) and the Society of St. Vincent de Paul (SVdP) entered into a Memorandum of Understanding during Fall 2017 in response to a determined need to strengthen the on-going and innovative collaborative relationship between the two partners.  My jointly funded position was created to support the development of mutually beneficial outcomes.  

As you may know, St. Vincent de Paul’s mission is to Feed, Clothe, House, and Heal individuals in need and to provide opportunities for the community to positively impact those in need through service.  The organization serves individuals on the poverty line but also those who experience chronic homelessness.  The no barrier overflow shelter in Maricopa County that is housed within the St. Vincent de Paul Downtown Phoenix Dining Room is set to close in September, as a result of funders reallocating funding to more permanent housing solutions.  Closing of the shelter has placed even more urgency around finding successful ways to divert or reunify individuals experiencing homelessness.  

We know that Miracle Messages presents an amazing opportunity to help reconnect those individuals experiencing homelessness with their families thereby ending their homelessness.  The SVdP & ASU Partnership has a unique opportunity to partner with an ASU Faculty, Professor Sandy Price, in the ASU College of Public Service & Community Solutions to pilot a program similar to Miracle Messages in her Nonprofit Leadership & Management (NLM) 160 – Voluntary Action & Community Leadership Course.  

We are would appreciate an opportunity to talk with the Kevin Adler, Jess Donig, and the rest of the Miracle Messages team to learn more about the operations of Miracle Messages and see how we may partner to support a similar effort in Phoenix, Arizona.  

Looking forward to hearing from you. 

Thank you, 

Erica Schwartzmann

Comment: I'm deeply impressed with your organization and your ongoing results. I've worked as a volunteer for three years at the Downtown Women's Center on Skid Row, where the motto is "Every Woman Housed.".  My sense is that re-housing our homeless population is the first and foremost best way to address this condition.My life long town, Santa Monica, has for many decades been referred to as "The Home of the Homeless" and our residents are reaching now critical mass in protest as homelessness keeps increasing here as everywhere else. Many of our current residents are fairly new to homelessness and at wits end not knowing how to proceed. I'm interested in bringing your organization and approach to the attention of our city leaders as they are putting forth attempts yet falling short in many ways in addressing the situation. Your approach is the most logical and practical in my estimation and I think if instituted here (we have lots of money!) it could very well be a shining beacon for expansion of Miracle Messages throughout the USA and beyond. I'm going to attend a community forum tomorrow. I'm not impressed that the instruction to business owners and residents is to "show up and be ready to listen and ask questions" as there is no room indicated for a well-rounded discussion that includes suggestions from residents. Please let me know your thoughts on this and I'm happy to be involved in bridging Miracle Messages to the City. My sense is it could be very successful! Thank you,Melissa Ward

That summer I noticed that a root cause of women forced into the sex trafficking business, is poverty and homelessness.  Our approach then was to hire victims of trafficking and offer them employment as well as a creative means (in forms of live performances) to express and heal from their suffering.

I imagine this internship would be a great way to start on a grassroots and community level.  I want to make change and feel like the work I'm doing amounts to impactful differences for other people.

Hi. I’m chronically homeless. I’m transgender and I have two bachelors degrees. I’m going back to the streets in a couple months. I’m nervous. Since Trump was elected I have gotten only a part time job at Giants stadium but got let go because I reported an employee who stole my medication. He kept refusing to call me by my gender and threw my meds away. I lost my roof last year because I fed the homeless. I have documented proof. But long story short, I love what you do. I’m homeless but I’m educated. I get rejected for that too. But I like to help to empower those with no power. I try to get people to vote. And y’all can look down on me but I have one vote just like you! But I dream of getting my PhD someday. I just need to get my life together. A job is that path. I have missed connections out there as well. Some died. I’m alone. It’s not safe. But my friends who didn’t abandon me, died. So I’m alone. But I’m the nicest, funniest, smartest person on the streets. I think I can be helpful. I just want to make the world better. I’m hated by so many who don’t understand that I too am deserving of equal rights. My heart is always broken. But my heart is true I promise you. Ciao!
